Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pop the @sweet potato{300%g}(diced) on a #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{drizzle} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat and roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden on the outside and soft in the middle, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim the @spring onion{1}(trimmed and sliced) then slice thinly. Heat a large #sauce pan{} on medium heat (no oil) and add the @flaked almonds{15%g}. Toast until golden ~{2-3%minutes}.

> Watch the almonds like a hawk as they can burn easily.

Once toasted, transfer to a #small bowl{} and set aside.

Put the sauce pan back onto a medium-high heat and add a drizzle of @oil{drizzle}. Add the onion and cook for until golden, stirring occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the garlic and @harissa paste{50%g} and cook for a further ~{1%minute}. Pour in the @water{200%ml} (see ingredients for amount), @vegetable stock powder{1%tbsp} and @chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1}(finely chopped). Bring to a boil, reduce the heat to medium, and simmer until it has thickened slightly, ~{7-8%minutes}. Stir occasionally.

Meanwhile, drain and rinse the @black beans{1%can} in a #colander{}. When the sauce has cooked down, add the black beans and @kale{100%g}(chopped) stirring occasionally. Continue to simmer until the stew has thickened and the kale stalks are tender, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Once the sweet potato is cooked, remove it from the oven and stir it through your stew. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Add a splash of @water{splash} if it's too thick.

Divide the bean stew between your #bowls{}. Finish with a dollop of @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} and generously sprinkle on the toasted almonds and spring onion. Enjoy!